\cf0 Audit and Remediate Cloudflare Worker Automation in Ignite\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa321\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 Cloudflare Workers Deployment Audit for Project Ignite\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Overview of Ignite Cloud Workers Environment\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Project Ignite\'92s cloud environment currently utilizes multiple Cloudflare Workers (and one Google Cloud Function) to automate tasks and services. The Workers are intended to operate together to form an autonomous system. Key components include a 
\f1\b Master Control Program (MCP) server
\f0\b0 , supporting microservice \'93agent\'94 workers, an 
\f1\b IDP (Identity Provider)
\f0\b0  service for authentication, a 
\f1\b mobile UI worker
\f0\b0  for control and status, a 
\f1\b Slack approval
\f0\b0  webhook worker, a 
\f1\b documentation/logging
\f0\b0  worker, and an 
\f1\b Okta\'96Ramp sync
\f0\b0  function on GCP. Each has its own configuration and deployment. This audit examines which Workers are deployed, identifies duplicate or conflicting directory structures, verifies the presence and config of each key worker, and reviews all 
\f2\fs26 wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24  files for consistency. Discrepancies and missing configurations are noted, followed by recommendations to clean up and fully automate the system.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Active Deployed Workers and Their Status\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Master Control Program (MCP) Worker:
\f0\b0  The core orchestrator is implemented as a Cloudflare Worker (in the 
\f2\fs26 mcp/
\f0\fs24  directory). Its Wrangler config shows it is named \'93project-ignite-mcp\'94 and binds to a Cloudflare D1 database (
\f2\fs26 mcp-store
\f0\fs24 ) and KV store (
\f2\fs26 MCP_STORE
\f0\fs24 ){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp/wrangler.toml#L10-L18"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp/wrangler.toml#L20-L23"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This MCP worker coordinates autonomous tasks and integrates with \'93agent\'94 workers. Currently, it is deployed to the 
\f2\fs26 *.workers.dev
\f0\fs24  domain (using 
\f2\fs26 workers_dev = true
\f0\fs24 ) without a custom route{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp/wrangler.toml#L6-L14"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. Environment variables like 
\f2\fs26 MCP_VERSION
\f0\fs24 , concurrency limits, and task timeouts are defined{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp/wrangler.toml#L10-L18"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This worker should be running as the central brain, but previously it appears to have been run in dev mode with external scripts to keep it alive (indicating it may not have been persistently deployed){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp/README.md#L38-L47"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. Ensuring this MCP service is deployed in production (not just via 
\f2\fs26 wrangler dev
\f0\fs24 ) is critical for autonomy.\

\f1\b MCP Mobile UI Worker:
\f0\b0  There is a worker providing a lightweight web UI (in 
\f2\fs26 mcp-mobile/
\f0\fs24  directory) intended for mobile or browser use. Its config name is \'93ignite-mcp-mobile\'94 with a route at 
\f2\fs26 mcp.project-ignite.kd8jc7v8cd.workers.dev/*{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/wrangler.toml#L12-L19"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24  (a workers.dev subdomain). The code uses the Hono framework to serve a control panel interface and API endpoints{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L9-L18"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L112-L120"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. It implements an HTML dashboard (\'93MCP Control\'94) with status, active deployments, logs, and quick-action buttons (Deploy, Rollback, Approve, Reject, etc.){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L137-L145"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L151-L160"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. The UI obtains an OAuth token from the IDP service on load and uses it to authorize API calls{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L184-L193"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L232-L240"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. The 
\f2\fs26 /api/status
\f0\fs24  and 
\f2\fs26 /api/quick-action
\f0\fs24  routes on this worker are protected by JWT middleware and are supposed to fetch system status and perform actions{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L39-L48"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L55-L64"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. However, in the current code, functions like 
\f2\fs26 getActiveDeployments
\f0\fs24 , 
\f2\fs26 getPendingTasks
\f0\fs24 , and 
\f2\fs26 executeQuickAction
\f0\fs24  are referenced but not defined within the mobile worker{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L41-L49"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L65-L73"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This suggests the mobile UI is expecting the MCP server or another service to handle those requests (likely via an internal API or dispatch call), but no such call is implemented. In other words, the mobile worker\'92s backend logic for those actions is incomplete \'96 a clear configuration gap that needs addressing so that quick-action buttons actually trigger behavior in the MCP system. The mobile worker\'92s 
\f2\fs26 wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24  also has a KV binding 
\f2\fs26 MOBILE_STATE
\f0\fs24  with placeholder IDs (
\f2\fs26 ignite-mobile-state
\f0\fs24 ) instead of a real namespace ID{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/wrangler.toml#L6-L14"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, indicating that either the KV store was not properly created or the config wasn\'92t updated with the actual ID. Additionally, the config defines production vars in two places (once inline and once under 
\f2\fs26 [env.production.vars]
\f0\fs24 ){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/wrangler.toml#L12-L20"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, which is redundant/misconfigured \'96 all prod vars should be consolidated under the 
\f2\fs26 env.production.vars
\f0\fs24  table. Despite these issues, the mobile UI worker is present and can be made functional with proper integration to the MCP backend.\

\f1\b IDP (Identity Provider) Worker:
\f0\b0  The IDP service (in 
\f2\fs26 mcp-idp/
\f0\fs24  directory) issues and verifies JWT tokens for authenticating the MCP UI and possibly other clients. Its config name is \'93ignite-mcp-idp\'94 with a route at 
\f2\fs26 idp.project-ignite.kd8jc7v8cd.workers.dev/*{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/wrangler.toml#L12-L19"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24 . It binds a KV store 
\f2\fs26 CLIENTS
\f0\fs24  (for client credentials){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/wrangler.toml#L6-L10"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. The IDP worker\'92s code provides an OAuth2-like token endpoint and introspection endpoint{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L29-L38"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L56-L65"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. It currently defines a single client (
\f2\fs26 mcp-mobile
\f0\fs24 ) with a secret from the environment (
\f2\fs26 MCP_MOBILE_SECRET
\f0\fs24 ) and only supports the client_credentials grant type{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L17-L25"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L34-L42"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. When a POST to 
\f2\fs26 /token
\f0\fs24  is received with the correct 
\f2\fs26 client_id
\f0\fs24  and 
\f2\fs26 client_secret
\f0\fs24 , it returns a signed JWT access token (using a shared 
\f2\fs26 JWT_SECRET
\f0\fs24 ) valid for one hour{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L45-L53"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L76-L85"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. The IDP also offers 
\f2\fs26 /introspect
\f0\fs24  to verify a token\'92s validity{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L56-L65"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This worker is present and configured, but it relies on secrets that must be set via Wrangler (both the JWT signing secret and the client\'92s secret). We should ensure those secrets are indeed defined (currently the config just leaves them blank placeholders{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/wrangler.toml#L30-L37"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}). Also, the allowed CORS origin is set to the mobile UI\'92s URL{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L8-L16"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, which is correct. Overall, the IDP component is in place and functioning as the auth server, but it requires the secret configuration to be aligned with the mobile UI (the same 
\f2\fs26 JWT_SECRET
\f0\fs24  must be used on both IDP and mobile worker to validate tokens, and the 
\f2\fs26 MCP_MOBILE_SECRET
\f0\fs24  must match what the mobile worker uses in its client script){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L184-L193"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L198-L202"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}.\

\f1\b Slack Approval Worker:
\f0\b0  There is a Cloudflare Worker configured to handle Slack interactive message payloads for approvals (in 
\f2\fs26 slack-approval-worker/
\f0\fs24 ). Its wrangler config name is \'93slack-approval-worker\'94 with a route at 
\f2\fs26 slack-approval.project-ignite.workers.dev/*{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/wrangler.toml#L6-L11"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24 . (Notably, this route uses 
\f2\fs26 project-ignite.workers.dev
\f0\fs24  without the 
\f2\fs26 kd8jc7v8cd
\f0\fs24  subdomain, indicating an inconsistency in domain naming \'96 see the 
\f1\b Config Inconsistencies
\f0\b0  section below.) The Slack worker\'92s code is minimal: it verifies the Slack signing secret on incoming requests and then parses the interactive message payload{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/index.js#L26-L34"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. When a Slack button (e.g. \'93Approve\'94) is clicked, Slack will POST to 
\f2\fs26 /slack/approve
\f0\fs24  on this worker. The worker checks the signature and extracts the 
\f2\fs26 secretName
\f0\fs24  value from the action{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/index.js#L27-L35"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. Currently, the code only logs a TODO comment: 
\f3\i \'93Trigger backend update to set status=approved in 1Password for secretName\'94{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/index.js#L34-L42"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i0 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\i0 . It doesn\'92t yet call any backend service or API to actually perform the approval \'96 it simply responds to Slack with a confirmation message that the secret has been approved{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/index.js#L38-L43"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This means the Slack workflow is 
\f1\b not fully wired up
\f0\b0 : the \'93approval\'94 doesn\'92t propagate into the MCP system or any secrets store. The Slack worker is deployed (the route exists and a signing secret variable is expected{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/wrangler.toml#L6-L11"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}), but to complete its functionality, it should invoke an internal API (perhaps an MCP endpoint or a 1Password API) to actually activate whatever was pending approval. The absence of such integration is a misconfiguration or incomplete feature. Additionally, we must ensure the 
\f2\fs26 SLACK_SIGNING_SECRET
\f0\fs24  is set in its environment (currently a blank placeholder in config{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/wrangler.toml#L8-L11"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}).\

\f1\b Documentation Worker:
\f0\b0  The repository includes a 
\f2\fs26 documentation-worker/
\f0\fs24  directory which appears to be intended as a Cloudflare Worker that consumes logs and possibly generates documentation or audit logs. The config integration is unusual \'96 the main Project Ignite Wrangler config declares a 
\f1\b tail consumer
\f0\b0  binding for 
\f2\fs26 documentation-worker{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/wrangler.toml#L72-L76"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24 . This means the documentation worker is meant to receive log events (\'93tail\'94 events) from other workers automatically. The code confirms this: it defines an 
\f2\fs26 async tail(events, env, ctx)
\f0\fs24  handler that iterates through log events from other workers and prints or records them{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/documentation-worker/index.ts#L51-L60"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/documentation-worker/index.ts#L61-L70"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. However, the documentation worker\'92s implementation is currently using Node.js filesystem operations (via 
\f2\fs26 fs/promises
\f0\fs24 ) to write logs to a file (
\f2\fs26 ./logs/worker.log
\f0\fs24 ){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/documentation-worker/index.ts#L1-L9"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/documentation-worker/index.ts#L17-L25"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This is problematic because Cloudflare Workers 
\f1\b do not support writing to a local filesystem
\f0\b0  in production \'96 the use of 
\f2\fs26 fs
\f0\fs24  here only works in a local development context (Wrangler\'92s Node sandbox). If deployed to Cloudflare\'92s edge, these calls will fail or have no effect. In other words, the documentation worker is not properly configured for the cloud environment; it cannot actually write logs persistently in a Workers runtime. Likely this worker was used in dev mode to capture events to a local file, but in production a different approach is needed (e.g. writing to Durable Objects, KV, R2, or an external logging service). It\'92s not clear if the documentation worker is currently deployed as an active service \'96 there\'92s no separate 
\f2\fs26 wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24  for it visible, and it might rely solely on the 
\f2\fs26 tail_consumers
\f0\fs24  configuration to run. Regardless, its state is not fully functional in the cloud. We should either refactor it to store logs in a supported manner or disable this component to avoid confusion. The concept of forwarding logs for documentation is sound, but it requires a proper implementation (perhaps generating Confluence docs or summaries from logs, per project goals).\

\f1\b Okta\'96Ramp Sync Function (GCP):
\f0\b0  Outside of Cloudflare Workers, there is a Google Cloud Function 
\f2\fs26 oktaRampSync
\f0\fs24  (found under 
\f2\fs26 cloud_functions/oktaRampSync/
\f0\fs24 ). This function listens for Okta group membership change events and updates user roles in Ramp accordingly. The code confirms it handles Okta event webhooks: it checks for 
\f2\fs26 X-Okta-Verification-Challenge
\f0\fs24  in requests (to echo back for Okta\'92s validation){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/cloud_functions/oktaRampSync/main.js#L24-L28"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, then processes events by mapping Okta group names to Ramp roles and calling the Ramp API to assign roles{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/cloud_functions/oktaRampSync/main.js#L32-L40"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/cloud_functions/oktaRampSync/main.js#L40-L48"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. It retrieves a Ramp API token from GCP Secret Manager{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/cloud_functions/oktaRampSync/main.js#L9-L17"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This function is indeed part of the Ignite environment (as the FedRamp/Okta integration), but it runs on GCP rather than Cloudflare. We include it here because it\'92s a \'93worker\'94 in a broad sense. The presence of this code indicates it should be deployed on GCP and integrated with Okta\'92s event hooks. We should verify if it\'92s active: specifically, whether an Okta event hook is pointing to the function\'92s endpoint and if the GCP function is up-to-date. Configuration-wise, ensure the GCP project and secret names (like 
\f2\fs26 ramp_api_token
\f0\fs24 ) are correct{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/cloud_functions/oktaRampSync/main.js#L10-L18"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This component appears properly coded; the main concern is making sure it\'92s deployed and not duplicated elsewhere (there\'92s no duplicate directory for it, but see below regarding naming).\

\f1\b Agent Workers:
\f0\b0  In addition to the above, the MCP architecture includes several 
\f1\b agent
\f0\b0  workers that handle specialized tasks (security orchestration, infrastructure, etc.). The repository\'92s 
\f2\fs26 scripts/deploy_mcp.sh
\f0\fs24  enumerates agent names such as \'93soc-coordinator,\'94 \'93security-agent,\'94 and \'93infrastructure-agent,\'94 deploying any worker found under 
\f2\fs26 agents/
\f0\fs24  subfolders{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/scripts/deploy_mcp.sh#L46-L54"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/scripts/deploy_mcp.sh#L56-L64"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. These agent workers are part of making the system autonomous by performing domain-specific actions under the MCP\'92s coordination. We did not see their detailed configs in this audit (they likely have their own 
\f2\fs26 wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24  in each agent\'92s folder). It\'92s important to confirm each agent is configured with the correct bindings and environment for its role, and that the MCP server knows about them. Notably, the deploy script posts a JSON to the MCP server\'92s 
\f2\fs26 /configure
\f0\fs24  endpoint to register these agents and enable 
\f2\fs26 autonomous_mode: true{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/scripts/deploy_mcp.sh#L42-L50"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/scripts/deploy_mcp.sh#L62-L70"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24 . This implies the MCP server has a 
\f2\fs26 /configure
\f0\fs24  API that stores agent info (likely in KV or D1) and toggles autonomy. For completeness, verifying that this 
\f2\fs26 /configure
\f0\fs24  endpoint exists in the MCP code and that autonomous mode truly functions is another step (outside the scope of this question\'92s key points, but critical for full system operation). The presence of agent directories should also be checked for duplicates or misnamed entries (the README in 
\f2\fs26 mcp/
\f0\fs24  notes that an older 
\f2\fs26 agents/orchestrator.js
\f0\fs24  was removed in cleanup{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp/README.md#L68-L73"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, which is good).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Duplicate and Conflicting Directories\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 During the audit, we identified a few naming inconsistencies that could indicate duplicate or outdated directories:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 cloud_functions/
\f1\fs24  vs 
\f4\fs26 cloud-functions/
\f1\fs24 :
\f0\b0  The repository uses 
\f2\fs26 cloud_functions/
\f0\fs24  (underscore) to house GCP Cloud Function code. In fact, the 
\f2\fs26 __init__.py
\f0\fs24  file inside it explicitly notes it \'93makes the cloud-functions directory a Python package.\'94 The mixed use of underscore vs. hyphen suggests a rename at some point. We did not find a separate 
\f2\fs26 cloud-functions/
\f0\fs24  folder in the latest tree, but the comment implies earlier naming might have been 
\f2\fs26 cloud-functions
\f0\fs24 . It\'92s possible one of these is vestigial. We should ensure only one consistent directory is used for cloud function code. Right now, all GCP functions (like OktaRampSync) are under 
\f2\fs26 cloud_functions/
\f0\fs24 . If an old path 
\f2\fs26 cloud-functions
\f0\fs24  exists or is referenced in documentation or build scripts, it should be consolidated to prevent confusion. This might be a minor issue if everything already points to 
\f2\fs26 cloud_functions/
\f0\fs24  \'96 the main action is to double-check that no build or deploy process is looking for the wrong directory name.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 mcp-idp
\f1\fs24  vs 
\f4\fs26 mcp-mobile
\f1\fs24 :
\f0\b0  These two directories are not duplicates in content (one is the IDP auth service, the other the mobile UI), but the naming could confuse new developers. Both relate to the \'93MCP\'94 component but serve different purposes. We should confirm that each is necessary and referenced appropriately. They do interact \'96 for example, the IDP issues tokens used by mcp-mobile, and the IDP\'92s client config is literally named \'93mcp-mobile\'94{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/index.js#L17-L25"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. The existence of both is deliberate: 
\f1\b mcp-idp
\f0\b0  handles authentication, while 
\f1\b mcp-mobile
\f0\b0  provides the UI and API gateway for controlling MCP. There is no functional conflict between them, but any overlapping configuration needs attention. For instance, 
\f1\b both
\f0\b0  workers rely on the same JWT secret and possibly the same admin credentials. It\'92s important that these values are not divergent. The 
\f2\fs26 ADMIN_USER
\f0\fs24 /
\f2\fs26 ADMIN_PASSWORD
\f0\fs24  that mcp-mobile expects (for login){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/wrangler.toml#L18-L25"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}} should correspond to a credential that the IDP would verify, but the current IDP implementation doesn\'92t use those \'96 it only checks a client secret. This suggests a potential 
\f1\b misalignment in authentication flow
\f0\b0 : either implement a proper user/password check (e.g., have IDP verify ADMIN_USER/PASSWORD and issue token) or clarify that the client secret itself is effectively the \'93password.\'94 Right now the mobile UI uses 
\f2\fs26 CLIENT_ID
\f0\fs24  and 
\f2\fs26 CLIENT_SECRET
\f0\fs24  in the frontend script (embedding the secret){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L184-L193"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L198-L202"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}} which is not a best practice for user login. Possibly, they intended to treat the single admin as an OAuth client. This is workable but should be clearly documented. In summary, 
\f1\b mcp-idp vs mcp-mobile
\f0\b0  aren\'92t duplicates to merge, but their configs must be consistent (same JWT_SECRET etc.) and the authentication design might need cleanup for clarity and security.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Aside from those, we did not see other duplicate directories with conflicting content. (For example, there is an 
\f2\fs26 ai-orchestrator
\f0\fs24  separate from the main 
\f2\fs26 ai
\f0\fs24  environment mentioned in wrangler, but that seems intentional as a distinct service for AI tasks.) It\'92s worth scanning for any leftover old directories (the context mentions a planned structure under 
\f2\fs26 services/
\f0\fs24  which no longer exists{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/context/project-truth.txt#L31-L39"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, implying the current layout evolved; ensure no orphaned directories from that prior structure remain).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Configuration Issues and Inconsistencies in Wrangler Files\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 All Cloudflare Workers in Project Ignite use Wrangler for configuration, but there are some inconsistencies and likely misconfigurations across their 
\f2\fs26 wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24  files:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Environment Routes and Domains:
\f0\b0  The workers do not use a single uniform domain schema. For example, the IDP and mobile workers use the 
\f2\fs26 kd8jc7v8cd.workers.dev
\f0\fs24  subdomain (e.g. 
\f2\fs26 idp.project-ignite.kd8jc7v8cd.workers.dev
\f0\fs24 ){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/wrangler.toml#L12-L19"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, whereas the Slack worker uses 
\f2\fs26 project-ignite.workers.dev
\f0\fs24  without the random subdomain string{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/wrangler.toml#L6-L11"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. One of these is likely incorrect. If the account\'92s Workers subdomain has been set to \'93project-ignite\'94, then all routes should be 
\f2\fs26 *.project-ignite.workers.dev
\f0\fs24  (no kd8\'85). In that case, the IDP and MCP-Mobile routes should probably be 
\f2\fs26 idp.project-ignite.workers.dev
\f0\fs24  and 
\f2\fs26 mcp.project-ignite.workers.dev
\f0\fs24  respectively. Alternatively, if the official subdomain is the 
\f2\fs26 kd8jc7v8cd
\f0\fs24  one, then Slack\'92s route definition is wrong. We need to clarify which subdomain is active for the Cloudflare account and update all 
\f2\fs26 route
\f0\fs24  entries to match. This ensures each service is reachable. It\'92s likely that the custom subdomain \'93project-ignite\'94 is intended (Slack\'92s config suggests it), so we should migrate IDP and mobile to that for consistency. Having mismatched domains can cause some workers to not receive traffic or to be deployed to unintended URLs.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 KV Namespace IDs and Bindings:
\f0\b0  Several workers use KV storage but not all configs have proper IDs:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The MCP server (project-ignite-mcp) binds 
\f2\fs26 MCP_STORE
\f0\fs24  with a specific namespace ID (c7eba0c8\'85 in both env and preview){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp/wrangler.toml#L20-L23"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This looks correct.\
\ls3\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The IDP binds a 
\f2\fs26 CLIENTS
\f0\fs24  KV with an ID (9dac31a0\'85) for production and uses the same for preview{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/wrangler.toml#L6-L14"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, which is fine.\
\ls3\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The MCP-Mobile binds 
\f2\fs26 MOBILE_STATE
\f0\fs24 , but 
\f1\b instead of a UUID it has 
\f4\fs26 "ignite-mobile-state"
\f1\fs24  and 
\f4\fs26 "ignite-mobile-state-preview"
\f0\b0\fs24  as the 
\f2\fs26 id
\f0\fs24  and 
\f2\fs26 preview_id{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/wrangler.toml#L6-L14"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24 . This is not a valid KV namespace ID \'96 it looks like a placeholder or title. Cloudflare KV expects a UUID for each namespace in Wrangler config. Possibly the developer meant to create a namespace named \'93ignite-mobile-state\'94 but didn\'92t update the config with its generated ID. This needs correction: create the KV store via 
\f2\fs26 wrangler kv:namespace create
\f0\fs24  (if not done) and put the actual IDs in 
\f2\fs26 wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24 . If the mobile worker doesn\'92t actually require persistent state yet, an alternate resolution is to remove the KV binding until needed. As it stands, this is misconfigured and could cause deployment errors or simply no-op binding.\
\ls3\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Also, ensure that if multiple workers need access to the same data, they either share a KV or use Durable Objects. For instance, \'93active deployments\'94 might be tracked in MCP\'92s KV or D1 \'96 the mobile UI might need to read it. Instead of giving mobile its own KV, it could read the MCP\'92s KV or query the MCP service. Deciding this affects config: if shared, one could bind 
\f2\fs26 MCP_STORE
\f0\fs24  to mobile as well (read-only) or provide an API.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Environment Variable Definitions:
\f0\b0  We observed inconsistent patterns. In 
\f2\fs26 mcp-idp/wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24 , a 
\f2\fs26 [vars]
\f0\fs24  section is used for dev defaults and secrets (with empty placeholders) and then 
\f2\fs26 [env.production.vars]
\f0\fs24  overrides the environment name{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-idp/wrangler.toml#L30-L37"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. In 
\f2\fs26 mcp-mobile/wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24 , the author placed 
\f2\fs26 vars = \{ ENVIRONMENT = "production" \}
\f0\fs24  under 
\f2\fs26 [env.production]
\f0\fs24  and then separately listed secrets under 
\f2\fs26 [env.production.vars]{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/wrangler.toml#L12-L20"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24 . The latter approach is redundant and possibly incorrect usage. The proper approach is to have 
\f1\b one
\f0\b0  
\f2\fs26 [env.production.vars]
\f0\fs24  table containing all needed variables. We should merge those so that 
\f2\fs26 ENVIRONMENT
\f0\fs24 , 
\f2\fs26 JWT_SECRET
\f0\fs24 , 
\f2\fs26 ADMIN_USER
\f0\fs24 , etc., all live under the env\'92s vars. Also, any secret values (like JWT_SECRET) should 
\f1\b not
\f0\b0  be given in plaintext in the toml \'96 they should be set via 
\f2\fs26 wrangler secret
\f0\fs24  and referenced by the code at runtime (which the team has partly done by leaving them blank). So the action item is to clean up these definitions for clarity.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Missing Triggers or Bindings:
\f0\b0  The root 
\f2\fs26 wrangler.toml
\f0\fs24  (Project Ignite global) defines CRON triggers for \'93ETL functions at 2:00 CDT\'94 and \'93monitorBudget every 15 minutes\'94{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/wrangler.toml#L20-L28"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. We need to verify that the corresponding code exists to handle these cron events. If the root worker (name 
\f2\fs26 project-ignite
\f0\fs24 ) is still deployed and contains scheduled task logic, it should have handlers for those schedules (perhaps in its 
\f2\fs26 index.js
\f0\fs24 ). If not, these triggers might be remnants that do nothing. Since our focus is on the Cloudflare Workers, note that having a main worker with scheduled tasks overlapping with the new MCP/agents design could be duplicative. If, for example, budget monitoring moved to an agent or GCP, the cron in Cloudflare should be removed to avoid confusion. We should locate or implement the functions for ETL and budget monitoring within whichever service is responsible (MCP or separate function) and adjust triggers accordingly.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Dispatch Namespace Usage:
\f0\b0  The root config also hints at use of Cloudflare\'92s 
\f1\b Services/Dispatch
\f0\b0  feature \'96 it defines a dispatch namespace \'93ignite-dispatcher-namespace\'94 bound as 
\f2\fs26 dispatcher{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/wrangler.toml#L70-L76"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}
\f0\fs24 , and even ties the 
\f2\fs26 ai-worker
\f0\fs24  environment to that dispatcher{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/wrangler.toml#L54-L62"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. This suggests the intention to route calls between different workers internally (for example, the MCP worker calling the documentation worker or AI worker via service binding instead of external HTTP). However, in the code we reviewed, we did not see explicit usage of 
\f2\fs26 env.dispatcher
\f0\fs24  or service binding calls. It\'92s possible this is still experimental or partially implemented. If dispatch is to be used, each service needs to be associated with that namespace in Cloudflare\'92s settings and looked up by name. For instance, logs might be dispatched to 
\f2\fs26 documentation-worker
\f0\fs24  service internally. Right now, the documentation worker tail consumer is configured via wrangler (which might actually rely on the dispatch namespace internally). We should verify that the services (documentation-worker, possibly MCP or AI orchestrator) are properly registered with the dispatch namespace. If not using dispatch, these config entries might be unnecessary and could be removed to simplify configuration. In short, clarify whether Cloudflare Service bindings are a part of Ignite\'92s architecture or if standard HTTP calls are used between workers, and then streamline the config accordingly.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 AI Worker Configuration:
\f0\b0  Although not explicitly asked, it\'92s worth noting the presence of an 
\f2\fs26 env.ai
\f0\fs24  configuration in the main Wrangler file{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/wrangler.toml#L46-L55"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}, which defines an 
\f2\fs26 ai-worker
\f0\fs24  service on route 
