\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Align Authentication Flow (MCP-Mobile & IDP):
\f0\b0  Revisit how the admin user authenticates to the MCP control panel. Right now, the system uses OAuth client credentials implicitly, which results in the client secret being present in the frontend code{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/mcp-mobile/index.js#L184-L193"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}}. To make the system more secure and user-friendly:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Implement a proper login on the MCP-Mobile UI: e.g., a form where admin enters username and password. The mobile worker can then verify those against the 
\f2\fs26 ADMIN_USER
\f0\fs24 /
\f2\fs26 ADMIN_PASSWORD
\f0\fs24  (either directly in the worker or by calling a new IDP endpoint) and then request a token from IDP using the client credentials (which the worker, not the browser, knows). Or the IDP could be extended to support a password grant or a custom admin token endpoint.\
\ls4\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 If maintaining the client_credentials approach, at least hide the secret from the client. You could have the MCP-Mobile worker perform the token fetch server-side (in the 
\f2\fs26 .fetch
\f0\fs24  handler upon a login request) rather than exposing it in the delivered HTML/JS.\
\ls4\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Ensure that the JWT secret is the same on both sides and consider rotating it if it was exposed during development.\
\ls4\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 These changes will solidify the IDP/Mobile interaction and remove confusion around credentials.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Complete Slack Approval Integration:
\f0\b0  The Slack approval workflow needs finishing so it truly connects to the system:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Decide where approved secrets or deployments are recorded. The Slack worker code suggests updating 1Password status for a secret{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/slack-approval-worker/index.js#L34-L42"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}} \'96 if 1Password is used to hold pending secrets or flags, integrate with its API here. Alternatively, if this was meant to approve a deployment in the MCP system, have the Slack worker call an MCP server API (e.g., an endpoint that marks a deployment as approved, which the MCP should then act on).\
\ls4\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Implement that call in the Slack worker and configure any needed credentials (if calling external APIs, possibly store a 1Password API token or have MCP provide a webhook).\
\ls4\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 After implementation, update the Slack interactive message setup (on Slack\'92s side) if needed to point to the correct URL (it seems to be already pointing to 
\f2\fs26 /slack/approve
\f0\fs24 ). Then test end-to-end: trigger a Slack approval request and ensure it results in the intended action (a secret being activated or a deployment proceeding) with confirmation back to Slack. Without this, the \'93approval\'94 step remains a manual gap.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	7	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Deploy the Documentation Worker or Replace It:
\f0\b0  Decide what to do with the documentation-worker:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Option A:
\f0\b0  Adapt it for Cloudflare\'92s environment. This likely means removing Node.js file operations and instead using a Durable Object or R2 bucket to accumulate logs. For example, the 
\f2\fs26 tail()
\f0\fs24  events could be written to a Durable Object that appends to an in-memory list or writes to R2 for long-term storage. Another approach: use Logpush or an external logging service rather than a worker to gather logs. If documentation-worker\'92s goal was to generate Confluence documentation from usage, clarify that requirement and implement accordingly (perhaps having it trigger on certain events or scheduled to summarize logs).\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Option B:
\f0\b0  If comprehensive logging isn\'92t a current priority, disable the tail consumer. You can remove the 
\f2\fs26 [[tail_consumers]]
\f0\fs24  entry from the main config{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/JW-Flo/Project-Ignite/blob/bcc8b784cac1d7962ed21c17e65e0b28a3998130/wrangler.toml#L74-L79"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 github.com}} to stop forwarding logs, and not deploy the documentation-worker at all. This avoids running a broken worker. Documentation can then be generated by other means if needed.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Regardless of approach, eliminate the current misconfiguration of using 
\f2\fs26 fs
